1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:00,720
No lawyer.

2
00:00:01,020 --> 00:00:02,020
A borrowed pencil.

3
00:00:02,620 --> 00:00:03,613
One prisoner —

4
00:00:03,940 --> 00:00:05,400
about to beat the Supreme Court.

5
00:00:05,980 --> 00:00:07,000
Nine to nothing.

6
00:00:11,280 --> 00:00:14,360
In 1963, almost no one in America had

7
00:00:14,360 --> 00:00:16,680
heard the name Clarence Earl Gideon.

8
00:00:17,460 --> 00:00:19,880
He was a drifter, in and out of

9
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:22,700
trouble his whole life, sitting in a Florida

10
00:00:22,700 --> 00:00:25,180
cell for a crime he swore he did

11
00:00:25,180 --> 00:00:25,820
not commit.

12
00:00:26,620 --> 00:00:28,840
He had stood in a courtroom and asked

13
00:00:28,840 --> 00:00:32,884
the judge for one simple thing —

14
00:00:32,885 --> 00:00:33,385
a lawyer.

15
00:00:33,386 --> 00:00:33,440
The judge said no.

16
00:00:34,120 --> 00:00:37,240
And that single word, "no," is where this

17
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:38,820
story actually begins.

18
00:00:39,860 --> 00:00:41,620
Here is something most of us assume is

19
00:00:41,620 --> 00:00:44,480
just permanently true: that if you are

20
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:46,540
arrested and cannot afford a lawyer,

21
00:00:46,940 --> 00:00:48,400
the court has to give you one.

22
00:00:49,060 --> 00:00:51,020
We treat it like a feature built into

23
00:00:51,020 --> 00:00:52,220
America from the start.

24
00:00:52,660 --> 00:00:53,540
It was not.

25
00:00:54,260 --> 00:00:56,080
For most of this country's history,

26
00:00:56,520 --> 00:00:58,360
if you were too poor to hire a

27
00:00:58,360 --> 00:01:01,000
lawyer, you could be put on trial alone

28
00:01:05,530 --> 00:01:05,830
—

29
00:01:05,831 --> 00:01:06,331
one frightened person against a trained

30
00:01:06,332 --> 00:01:07,320
prosecutor whose entire job was to convict

31
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:07,840
you.

32
00:01:08,620 --> 00:01:10,860
The guarantee of a free lawyer is younger

33
00:01:10,860 --> 00:01:11,820
than your grandparents.

34
00:01:12,580 --> 00:01:15,180
And it exists because of one stubborn

35
00:01:15,180 --> 00:01:18,680
prisoner, one handwritten letter, and one

36
00:01:18,680 --> 00:01:21,540
unanimous decision in 1963.

37
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:25,260
Over the next twelve minutes: how a man

38
00:01:25,260 --> 00:01:28,260
nobody believed in forced the Supreme Court

39
00:01:28,260 --> 00:01:30,920
to rewrite the rules of every criminal trial

40
00:01:30,920 --> 00:01:32,664
in America —

41
00:01:32,665 --> 00:01:34,660
and the imperfect system that ruling left

42
00:01:34,660 --> 00:01:35,260
behind.

43
00:01:35,960 --> 00:01:37,600
Start in a Florida courtroom,

44
00:01:37,960 --> 00:01:38,940
1961.

45
00:01:40,140 --> 00:01:42,360
Clarence Earl Gideon is charged with

46
00:01:42,360 --> 00:01:45,060
breaking into a poolroom and stealing a

47
00:01:45,060 --> 00:01:46,585
little money and some bottles of drink —

48
00:01:47,560 --> 00:01:49,740
under Florida law, a felony.

49
00:01:50,360 --> 00:01:51,300
He is poor.

50
00:01:51,880 --> 00:01:54,040
He has been in and out of prison

51
00:01:54,040 --> 00:01:54,600
before.

52
00:01:55,180 --> 00:01:57,100
And he knows, the way you know a

53
00:01:57,100 --> 00:01:59,060
thing in your gut, that he cannot do

54
00:01:59,060 --> 00:01:59,640
this alone.

55
00:02:00,560 --> 00:02:02,620
So he asks the court to appoint a

56
00:02:02,620 --> 00:02:03,400
lawyer for him.

57
00:02:04,020 --> 00:02:05,960
The judge tells him the law does not

58
00:02:05,960 --> 00:02:08,483
allow it —

59
00:02:08,484 --> 00:02:08,960
in Florida at that time,

60
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:12,040
a free lawyer was provided only when a

61
00:02:12,040 --> 00:02:13,700
person's life was on the line,

62
00:02:14,200 --> 00:02:15,920
in a death-penalty case.

63
00:02:16,920 --> 00:02:18,680
Gideon's case is not one of those.

64
00:02:19,240 --> 00:02:21,640
The chair where his lawyer should sit stays

65
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:22,100
empty.

66
00:02:22,940 --> 00:02:24,920
Picture what a trial actually is.

67
00:02:25,280 --> 00:02:28,281
It is a contest with rules —

68
00:02:28,720 --> 00:02:30,940
rules about what evidence can come in,

69
00:02:31,460 --> 00:02:33,280
which questions can be asked,

70
00:02:33,640 --> 00:02:35,480
what a jury is allowed to hear.

71
00:02:36,400 --> 00:02:39,320
On one side stands a prosecutor who has

72
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:41,020
done this hundreds of times,

73
00:02:41,380 --> 00:02:43,500
who knows every one of those rules by

74
00:02:43,500 --> 00:02:43,820
heart.

75
00:02:44,620 --> 00:02:45,940
On the other side, now,

76
00:02:45,940 --> 00:02:49,760
stands Gideon: no training, no preparation,

77
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:53,160
trying to defend his own freedom in a

78
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:54,560
language he does not speak.

79
00:02:55,340 --> 00:02:56,220
He does his best.

80
00:02:56,800 --> 00:02:58,420
He makes an opening statement,

81
00:02:58,920 --> 00:03:01,780
he questions witnesses, he argues to the

82
00:03:01,780 --> 00:03:02,060
jury.

83
00:03:02,840 --> 00:03:04,860
But doing your best is not the same

84
00:03:04,860 --> 00:03:06,280
as knowing what you are doing.

85
00:03:06,920 --> 00:03:08,580
The verdict comes back guilty,

86
00:03:08,580 --> 00:03:10,860
and the court sends him to prison for

87
00:03:10,860 --> 00:03:11,560
five years.

88
00:03:12,340 --> 00:03:14,600
For almost anyone else, that is the end.

89
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:17,620
A poor man, convicted, locked away,

90
00:03:17,620 --> 00:03:18,360
out of moves.

91
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:21,380
But Gideon has one move left that no

92
00:03:21,380 --> 00:03:22,921
one expects —

93
00:03:22,922 --> 00:03:24,140
and it costs five cents.

94
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:27,280
In his cell, Gideon does something quietly

95
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:28,040
extraordinary.

96
00:03:28,840 --> 00:03:30,640
He gets hold of a pencil and some

97
00:03:30,640 --> 00:03:32,840
prison paper, and in careful,

98
00:03:32,840 --> 00:03:35,740
hand-printed letters he writes directly to

99
00:03:35,740 --> 00:03:38,846
the Supreme Court of the United States —

100
00:03:38,847 --> 00:03:40,500
asking them to hear his case.

101
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:43,180
He cannot pay the court's fees,

102
00:03:43,380 --> 00:03:45,740
so he files as what the law calls

103
00:03:45,740 --> 00:03:48,388
a pauper —

104
00:03:48,389 --> 00:03:48,900
a person too poor to pay.

105
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:51,340
No firm is behind him.

106
00:03:51,760 --> 00:03:53,900
No famous attorney is making calls.

107
00:03:54,620 --> 00:03:56,240
It is just one prisoner,

108
00:03:56,240 --> 00:04:00,212
arguing that what happened to him —

109
00:04:00,213 --> 00:04:02,659
being tried without a lawyer —

110
00:04:02,660 --> 00:04:04,160
was not just unlucky, but unconstitutional.

111
00:04:05,280 --> 00:04:07,340
And here is the wall standing directly in

112
00:04:07,340 --> 00:04:07,840
his way.

113
00:04:08,720 --> 00:04:11,640
Twenty years earlier, in a case called Betts

114
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:11,800
v.

115
00:04:12,300 --> 00:04:15,060
Brady, the Supreme Court had already looked

116
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:18,253
at almost this exact question —

117
00:04:18,254 --> 00:04:19,360
and had ruled the other way.

118
00:04:20,100 --> 00:04:22,100
Betts said that states did not have to

119
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:24,360
hand every poor defendant a lawyer.

120
00:04:25,080 --> 00:04:27,900
A free lawyer was required only in "special

121
00:04:27,900 --> 00:04:30,342
circumstances" —

122
00:04:30,343 --> 00:04:31,000
if you were very young,

123
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,020
or could not read, or the case was

124
00:04:34,020 --> 00:04:35,300
unusually complex.

125
00:04:36,280 --> 00:04:39,660
An ordinary poor man, in an ordinary case,

126
00:04:39,660 --> 00:04:41,860
was expected to manage on his own.

127
00:04:42,600 --> 00:04:45,100
So Gideon is not just asking the Court

128
00:04:45,100 --> 00:04:45,820
to help him.

129
00:04:46,380 --> 00:04:48,720
He is asking the most powerful court in

130
00:04:48,720 --> 00:04:50,720
the country to admit it had been wrong

131
00:04:52,749 --> 00:04:53,049
—

132
00:04:53,050 --> 00:04:54,860
to overturn its own decision and rewrite the

133
00:04:54,860 --> 00:04:56,460
rule for every state at once.

134
00:04:57,360 --> 00:04:59,620
Prisoners send the Supreme Court thousands

135
00:04:59,620 --> 00:05:02,180
of these handwritten petitions every year.

136
00:05:02,740 --> 00:05:05,160
The Court turns away almost all of them.

137
00:05:05,640 --> 00:05:07,580
It did not turn away Gideon's.

138
00:05:07,980 --> 00:05:10,956
The justices agreed to hear the case —

139
00:05:10,957 --> 00:05:12,960
and then did something that turns the whole

140
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:13,960
story on its head.

141
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:16,520
The man who had been denied a lawyer

142
00:05:16,520 --> 00:05:19,080
in Florida was now given one of the

143
00:05:19,080 --> 00:05:21,680
finest lawyers in America: the Court

144
00:05:21,680 --> 00:05:24,060
appointed a top Washington attorney named

145
00:05:24,060 --> 00:05:26,573
Abe Fortas —

146
00:05:26,574 --> 00:05:29,116
a future Supreme Court justice himself —

147
00:05:29,117 --> 00:05:29,920
to argue Gideon's side.

148
00:05:30,760 --> 00:05:33,220
The question was no longer just about one

149
00:05:33,220 --> 00:05:34,300
man in one cell.

150
00:05:34,960 --> 00:05:37,320
It had become a question about every poor

151
00:05:37,320 --> 00:05:38,700
defendant in the country.

152
00:05:39,440 --> 00:05:42,200
Did the Constitution promise them a lawyer,

153
00:05:42,200 --> 00:05:43,320
or didn't it?

154
00:05:43,980 --> 00:05:47,060
On March 18, 1963, the Supreme Court

155
00:05:47,060 --> 00:05:48,043
answered —

156
00:05:48,440 --> 00:05:50,220
and this time the answer was not close.

157
00:05:51,040 --> 00:05:52,580
The decision was unanimous.

158
00:05:53,120 --> 00:05:54,620
Every single justice agreed.

159
00:05:55,940 --> 00:05:57,960
Justice Hugo Black, writing for the Court,

160
00:05:57,960 --> 00:05:59,160
delivered the ruling.

161
00:05:59,900 --> 00:06:02,420
The reasoning was almost startlingly plain.

162
00:06:03,080 --> 00:06:05,980
The Sixth Amendment promises anyone accused

163
00:06:05,980 --> 00:06:08,844
of a crime "the assistance of counsel" —

164
00:06:10,260 --> 00:06:11,500
the help of a lawyer.

165
00:06:12,300 --> 00:06:14,720
The Court said that promise is not a

166
00:06:14,720 --> 00:06:16,260
luxury or a formality.

167
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:19,700
In our system, where the government hires

168
00:06:19,700 --> 00:06:22,240
trained prosecutors and builds courthouses

169
00:06:22,240 --> 00:06:23,860
and writes the rules of evidence,

170
00:06:24,640 --> 00:06:26,240
a lawyer is not a frill.

171
00:06:26,900 --> 00:06:29,655
A lawyer is a necessity —

172
00:06:29,656 --> 00:06:32,640
without one, the trial itself is not truly

173
00:06:32,640 --> 00:06:33,060
fair.

174
00:06:33,700 --> 00:06:36,180
And because a fair trial is a basic

175
00:06:36,180 --> 00:06:39,380
right, the Court held, that right cannot

176
00:06:39,380 --> 00:06:41,460
stop at the federal courthouse door.

177
00:06:42,480 --> 00:06:44,660
Through the Fourteenth Amendment, it binds

178
00:06:44,660 --> 00:06:45,580
the states too.

179
00:06:46,500 --> 00:06:48,980
From that day forward, any state putting a

180
00:06:48,980 --> 00:06:51,540
poor person on trial for a serious crime

181
00:06:51,540 --> 00:06:54,184
had to give that person a lawyer —

182
00:06:54,620 --> 00:06:56,380
and if they could not afford one,

183
00:06:56,880 --> 00:06:58,420
the state had to provide one.

184
00:06:59,160 --> 00:07:00,400
To say all of this,

185
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:02,640
the Court had to do the thing Gideon

186
00:07:02,640 --> 00:07:04,040
had dared to ask for.

187
00:07:04,500 --> 00:07:06,660
It reached back and overruled its own

188
00:07:06,660 --> 00:07:07,220
precedent.

189
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:08,560
Betts v.

190
00:07:09,020 --> 00:07:10,246
Brady —

191
00:07:10,247 --> 00:07:11,338
the wall —

192
00:07:11,339 --> 00:07:11,839
was knocked down.

193
00:07:11,840 --> 00:07:14,620
The old "special circumstances" test was

194
00:07:14,620 --> 00:07:15,000
gone.

195
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:17,920
The new rule was simple enough for anyone

196
00:07:17,920 --> 00:07:20,660
to understand: if you are too poor to

197
00:07:20,660 --> 00:07:23,340
hire a lawyer, the state must appoint one

198
00:07:23,340 --> 00:07:23,860
for you.

199
00:07:24,540 --> 00:07:26,940
A handwritten letter from a prison cell had

200
00:07:26,940 --> 00:07:29,060
just rewritten the law for the entire

201
00:07:29,060 --> 00:07:29,600
country.

202
00:07:30,300 --> 00:07:32,240
But it had not yet done the one

203
00:07:32,240 --> 00:07:34,100
thing Gideon cared about most.

204
00:07:34,740 --> 00:07:36,900
Because winning at the Supreme Court did not

205
00:07:36,900 --> 00:07:37,960
set Gideon free.

206
00:07:38,680 --> 00:07:41,660
It did something narrower: it threw out his

207
00:07:41,660 --> 00:07:44,620
conviction and sent him back to Florida for

208
00:07:44,620 --> 00:07:45,640
a brand-new trial.

209
00:07:46,360 --> 00:07:47,420
The same charges.

210
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:49,080
The same town.

211
00:07:49,760 --> 00:07:52,560
But this time, the empty chair was filled.

212
00:07:53,640 --> 00:07:56,380
Gideon walked into that second trial with an

213
00:07:56,380 --> 00:07:58,120
appointed lawyer beside him.

214
00:07:58,920 --> 00:08:00,640
And the difference was night and day.

215
00:08:01,380 --> 00:08:03,420
A real defense attorney picked the case

216
00:08:03,420 --> 00:08:05,069
apart —

217
00:08:05,070 --> 00:08:07,740
testing the witnesses, poking at the state's

218
00:08:07,740 --> 00:08:11,040
story, doing all the things Gideon had never

219
00:08:11,040 --> 00:08:12,160
known how to do alone.

220
00:08:12,840 --> 00:08:14,860
This time, the jury came back with a

221
00:08:14,860 --> 00:08:16,820
different word: not guilty.

222
00:08:17,560 --> 00:08:19,820
Sit with that contrast for a second.

223
00:08:20,460 --> 00:08:23,160
The very same man, facing the very same

224
00:08:23,160 --> 00:08:23,780
accusation.

225
00:08:24,620 --> 00:08:27,020
Alone, he was convicted and sent to prison.

226
00:08:27,740 --> 00:08:30,460
With a lawyer, he was acquitted and walked

227
00:08:30,460 --> 00:08:31,160
out free.

228
00:08:32,160 --> 00:08:33,940
Nothing about Gideon had changed.

229
00:08:34,620 --> 00:08:36,580
The only thing that changed was whether

230
00:08:36,580 --> 00:08:38,840
anyone in that room was standing on his

231
00:08:38,840 --> 00:08:39,300
side.

232
00:08:40,000 --> 00:08:41,010
That gap —

233
00:08:41,011 --> 00:08:44,140
between facing the state alone and facing it

234
00:08:44,140 --> 00:08:45,433
with help —

235
00:08:45,434 --> 00:08:47,600
is the entire reason the right exists.

236
00:08:48,360 --> 00:08:50,520
And Gideon's win did not stay with Gideon.

237
00:08:51,080 --> 00:08:53,520
His name became the key that unlocked the

238
00:08:53,520 --> 00:08:55,760
same right for everyone behind him.

239
00:08:56,700 --> 00:08:58,880
Across the country, states had to build

240
00:08:58,880 --> 00:09:00,860
something new to keep the promise the Court

241
00:09:00,860 --> 00:09:04,100
had just made: offices full of lawyers whose

242
00:09:04,100 --> 00:09:06,540
job is to defend people who cannot pay

243
00:09:07,841 --> 00:09:08,141
—

244
00:09:08,142 --> 00:09:08,340
the public defenders.

245
00:09:09,340 --> 00:09:11,400
If you have ever heard the phrase "a

246
00:09:11,400 --> 00:09:13,520
public defender will be assigned to you,"

247
00:09:13,900 --> 00:09:16,500
that system traces back, in large part,

248
00:09:16,500 --> 00:09:18,060
to a prisoner's pencil.

249
00:09:18,720 --> 00:09:20,920
But this is where the hidden room opens

250
00:09:21,971 --> 00:09:22,271
—

251
00:09:22,272 --> 00:09:23,540
and it is not a tidy victory.

252
00:09:24,440 --> 00:09:26,560
The Court could create the right with a

253
00:09:26,560 --> 00:09:27,600
stroke of the pen.

254
00:09:28,380 --> 00:09:30,300
It could not, with that same pen,

255
00:09:30,680 --> 00:09:31,320
pay for it.

256
00:09:32,120 --> 00:09:34,100
A right to a lawyer is only as

257
00:09:34,100 --> 00:09:36,180
real as the lawyer you actually get.

258
00:09:36,840 --> 00:09:38,460
And in the decades since,

259
00:09:38,600 --> 00:09:43,081
public defenders have often been buried —

260
00:09:43,082 --> 00:09:43,780
too many clients, too little money,

261
00:09:44,220 --> 00:09:45,800
too little time for each case.

262
00:09:46,360 --> 00:09:48,600
The promise is guaranteed on paper.

263
00:09:49,320 --> 00:09:50,640
Whether it is fully kept,

264
00:09:50,860 --> 00:09:54,360
case by case, still depends on resources no

265
00:09:54,360 --> 00:09:56,200
court can simply order into being.

266
00:09:56,940 --> 00:09:59,180
So Gideon answered the question Miranda

267
00:09:59,180 --> 00:10:00,760
would raise three years later.

268
00:10:01,520 --> 00:10:02,920
When a suspect is told,

269
00:10:03,640 --> 00:10:05,140
"if you cannot afford a lawyer,

270
00:10:05,620 --> 00:10:08,260
one will be appointed for you," those words

271
00:10:08,260 --> 00:10:09,200
are not a courtesy.

272
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:11,857
They are a promise —

273
00:10:11,858 --> 00:10:13,020
and it is Gideon's promise.

274
00:10:13,620 --> 00:10:16,360
Step back, and the shape of it is

275
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:17,540
almost hard to believe.

276
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:20,040
We did not get the right to a

277
00:10:20,040 --> 00:10:21,840
free lawyer from a great speech,

278
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:25,060
or a famous senator, or a crowd in

279
00:10:25,060 --> 00:10:25,540
the street.

280
00:10:26,380 --> 00:10:28,440
We got it because one poor,

281
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:32,060
twice-doubted prisoner refused to accept

282
00:10:32,060 --> 00:10:34,380
that justice was something only people with

283
00:10:34,380 --> 00:10:35,305
money could buy —

284
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:37,940
and because he wrote it down and mailed

285
00:10:37,940 --> 00:10:38,620
it in.

286
00:10:39,440 --> 00:10:41,660
Clarence Earl Gideon got the ending you

287
00:10:41,660 --> 00:10:42,680
almost never get.

288
00:10:43,280 --> 00:10:46,300
He won at the highest court in the

289
00:10:46,300 --> 00:10:49,040
land, and then he won his freedom too.

290
00:10:49,040 --> 00:10:52,620
But the thing he really won was never

291
00:10:52,620 --> 00:10:53,820
just for him.

292
00:10:53,820 --> 00:10:54,420
He won a rule —

293
00:10:55,800 --> 00:10:57,120
that in an American courtroom,

294
00:10:57,120 --> 00:10:59,360
you do not have to face the full

295
00:10:59,360 --> 00:11:00,229
weight of the state with an empty chair

296
00:11:00,262 --> 00:11:00,895
beside you.

297
00:11:00,896 --> 00:11:03,240
That is the hidden system behind a phrase

298
00:11:03,240 --> 00:11:04,720
you have heard a hundred times.

299
00:11:05,360 --> 00:11:07,600
"You have the right to an attorney" is

300
00:11:07,600 --> 00:11:08,700
not set dressing.

301
00:11:09,280 --> 00:11:11,440
It is a promise paid for by a

302
00:11:11,440 --> 00:11:16,110
prisoner with a pencil —

303
00:11:16,111 --> 00:11:17,600
powerful, real, and still, to this day,

304
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:18,500
unfinished.

305
00:11:19,660 --> 00:11:22,300
Next time, we open the door on who

306
00:11:22,300 --> 00:11:24,400
decides what counts as a crime in the

307
00:11:24,400 --> 00:11:25,120
first place.

308
00:11:25,720 --> 00:11:28,960
Until then: now you know who actually gets

309
00:11:28,960 --> 00:11:30,711
a lawyer —

310
00:11:30,712 --> 00:11:30,800
and why.
